    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-02-10T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-02-10T05:00:00-05:00" n="760"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d760">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.811/1096: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Canton</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Myers</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Canton</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-02-10T18:00:00+08:00"
                            >February 10, 1939—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 10—10:32 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>22. Reference my 21, February 5, 4 p.m. The Pearl River was reopened for movement
                    of foreign warships as from this morning. The landing of Japanese troops on
                        Hainan<note n="4" xml:id="d760fn4">See also <ref target="#pg_103">pp.
                            103</ref> ff.</note> seems to explain closure of the river.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Chungking, Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Myers</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
